  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the full syllabus and topics that I should cover for GMAT preparation?",
  "response": "The Graduate Management Admission Test (GMAT) is a standardized test used for admission into business school programs such as MBA (Master of Business Administration). The GMAT assesses a candidate's analytical, writing, quantitative, verbal, and reading skills in standard written English. Below is a detailed syllabus and list of topics you should cover for GMAT preparation:\n\n### GMAT Exam Format:\n1. **Analytical Writing Assessment (AWA)**\n2. **Integrated Reasoning (IR)**\n3. **Quantitative Section**\n4. **Verbal Section**\n\n### Detailed Syllabus:\n\n#### 1. Analytical Writing Assessment (AWA)\n- **Essay Writing:** \n  - Analysis of an Argument\n  - Assessing the reasoning behind an argument and writing a critique\n  - Focus on clarity, logic, coherence, and grammar\n\n#### 2. Integrated Reasoning (IR)\n- **Multi-Source Reasoning:** \n  - Analyze data from multiple sources (tables, graphs, texts)\n- **Table Analysis:** \n  - Sort and analyze data in a table format\n- **Graphics Interpretation:** \n  - Interpret data in graphs and other visual representations\n- **Two-Part Analysis:** \n  - Solve complex problems with two-part answers\n\n#### 3. Quantitative Section\n- **Problem Solving:**\n  - Arithmetic\n    - Number properties, operations, fractions, decimals, percent, ratios\n  - Algebra\n    - Linear equations, inequalities, quadratic equations, functions\n  - Geometry\n    - Lines, angles, triangles, circles, polygons, coordinate geometry\n  - Word Problems\n    - Rate and work, mixture, probability, sets, sequences\n\n- **Data Sufficiency:**\n  - Assessing whether given data is sufficient to answer a question\n  - Understanding the format and logical reasoning needed for data sufficiency questions\n\n#### 4. Verbal Section\n- **Reading Comprehension:**\n  - Main idea, details, inference, logical structure, author's tone\n  - Understanding and analyzing written content\n\n- **Critical Reasoning:**\n  - Argument construction and evaluation\n  - Identifying assumptions, evaluating argument strength, drawing conclusions\n\n- **Sentence Correction:**\n  - Grammar and usage\n  - Subject-verb agreement, parallelism, modifiers, verb tense, idiomatic expressions\n\n### Preparation Tips:\n1. **Understand the Exam Format:**\n   - Familiarize yourself with the structure and types of questions.\n   \n2. **Develop a Study Plan:**\n   - Allocate time for each section based on your strengths and weaknesses.\n   \n3. **Practice Regularly:**\n   - Use GMAT prep books, online resources, and practice tests.\n   - Analyze your performance to identify areas for improvement.\n   \n4. **Learn Test Strategies:**\n   - Time management, guessing strategies, and understanding common traps.\n   \n5. **Review Fundamentals:**\n   - Ensure a strong grasp of basic math concepts, grammar rules, and reading comprehension techniques.\n   \n6. **Consider Prep Courses:**\n   - If needed, enroll in GMAT prep courses or find a tutor.\n\nBy covering these topics systematically and practicing regularly, you can improve your chances of achieving a high score on the GMAT. Good luck with your preparation!",
